<Layout title="Module 3 – Patient Assessment">
  <h1>Module 3: Patient Assessment</h1>
  <p>
    A thorough, systematic assessment is the foundation of the nursing process. Data gathered
    guides planning, interventions, and evaluation of patient outcomes.
  </p>

  <h2>The Nursing Process (ADPIE)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>A</strong>ssessment — collect subjective and objective data</li>
    <li><strong>D</strong>iagnosis — identify nursing diagnoses (NANDA)</li>
    <li><strong>P</strong>lanning — establish goals and expected outcomes</li>
    <li><strong>I</strong>mplementation — perform nursing interventions</li>
    <li><strong>E</strong>valuation — determine whether goals were met; revise as needed</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Types of Data</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Subjective:</strong> What the patient reports (symptoms, feelings, history).</li>
    <li><strong>Objective:</strong> What the nurse observes, measures, or detects (signs, vital signs, lab results).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Head-to-Toe Physical Assessment</h2>
  <h3>General Survey</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Level of consciousness (LOC), appearance, affect, hygiene, apparent distress.</li>
    <li>Height, weight, BMI.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Neurological</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS): Eye opening (1–4) + Verbal response (1–5) + Motor response (1–6) = 3–15 total.</li>
    <li>Pupillary response: PERRLA (Pupils Equal, Round, Reactive to Light and Accommodation).</li>
    <li>Orientation: Person, place, time, event.</li>
    <li>Cranial nerve assessment as indicated.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cardiovascular</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Heart rate and rhythm; auscultate S1 and S2 at 4 landmarks (aortic, pulmonic, Erb's point, tricuspid, mitral).</li>
    <li>Peripheral pulses: Compare bilateral radial, brachial, femoral, popliteal, posterior tibial, dorsalis pedis.</li>
    <li>Edema: Grade 1+ (trace) to 4+ (severe, pitting).</li>
    <li>Capillary refill: Normal &lt; 2 seconds.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Respiratory</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Respiratory rate, depth, rhythm, and effort.</li>
    <li>Breath sounds: Vesicular (normal), bronchovesicular, bronchial, adventitious (crackles, wheezes, rhonchi, stridor, pleural friction rub).</li>
    <li>Oxygen saturation (SpO₂).</li>
    <li>Use of accessory muscles, nasal flaring, tripod positioning.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Gastrointestinal</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Inspect abdomen: Shape, symmetry, distension, visible peristalsis.</li>
    <li>Auscultate bowel sounds in all 4 quadrants (5 min per quadrant before reporting absence).</li>
    <li>Palpate: Tenderness, guarding, rigidity, masses.</li>
    <li>Last bowel movement and characteristics.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Genitourinary</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Urine output: Minimum 0.5 mL/kg/hr (adult); color, clarity, odor.</li>
    <li>Bladder distension assessment.</li>
    <li>Presence of urinary catheter — confirm catheter care performed per protocol.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Musculoskeletal</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Muscle strength: Grade 0 (no contraction) – 5 (full strength against resistance).</li>
    <li>Range of motion (ROM): Active vs. passive.</li>
    <li>Gait, balance, coordination.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Integumentary</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Color (pallor, cyanosis, jaundice, erythema), temperature, moisture, turgor.</li>
    <li>Lesions: ABCDE of melanoma (Asymmetry, Border, Color, Diameter, Evolution).</li>
    <li>Pressure injuries: Braden Scale (risk assessment) and staging (Stage I–IV, unstageable, deep tissue injury).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Pain Assessment</h2>
  <p>Pain is considered the fifth vital sign. Select a scale appropriate for the patient's age and cognitive status.</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Scale</th><th>Best Used For</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>NRS (0–10)</td>
        <td>Adults who can self-report</td>
        <td>0 = no pain; 10 = worst imaginable pain</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Wong-Baker FACES</td>
        <td>Children ≥ 3 yr; adults with literacy challenges</td>
        <td>Six faces from happy (0) to crying (10)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>FLACC</td>
        <td>Infants; non-verbal patients</td>
        <td>Scores Face, Legs, Activity, Cry, Consolability (0–10)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>CPOT</td>
        <td>Critically ill / sedated patients</td>
        <td>Critical-Care Pain Observation Tool (0–8)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 OLDCARTS Mnemonic</strong>
    Onset, Location, Duration, Characteristics, Aggravating factors, Relieving factors,
    Treatment, Severity — use to fully characterize any pain complaint.
  </div>

  <h2>Documentation</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Document findings promptly, accurately, and objectively.</li>
    <li>Use approved abbreviations per facility policy.</li>
    <li>Follow the facility's EHR (Electronic Health Record) charting structure.</li>
    <li>Report abnormal findings to the provider immediately and document the communication.</li>
    <li>Never chart care that was not given; never alter or delete prior entries.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ Legal Reminder</strong>
    The medical record is a legal document. Accurate, timely documentation protects the
    patient and the nurse. If it isn't charted, legally it wasn't done.
  </div>

  <h2>Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>ADPIE:</strong> Assessment, Diagnosis, Planning, Implementation, Evaluation — steps of the nursing process.</li>
    <li><strong>GCS:</strong> Glasgow Coma Scale — standardized neurological assessment tool.</li>
    <li><strong>Braden Scale:</strong> Risk assessment tool for pressure injury development.</li>
    <li><strong>NRS:</strong> Numeric Rating Scale for pain.</li>
    <li><strong>OLDCARTS:</strong> Mnemonic for comprehensive pain assessment.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
